{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"441da823-8f1e-43d4-802e-ba22fbc2c883","content":"Two things change with xUnit v3 + MTP:\n\n### 1. Filter syntax changes\n\nWith MTP, the executable **is** the test host, so you use `--filter` directly on the built binary (or via `dotnet test`/`dotnet run`), but the **operators** changed:\n\n| VSTest (v2) | MTP (v3) |\n|---|---|\n| `~` (contains) | `=*` (contains) |\n| `&` (and) | `&` (same) |\n| `Category` | `trait:Category` |\n\nYour new filter:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName=*IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\nOr if running the executable directly:\n\n```bash\n./TestProject --filter \"FullyQualifiedName=*IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n### 2. `[Trait]` → `[Category]` shortcut (optional)\n\nxUnit v3 ships a built-in `[Category]` attribute, so you can simplify:\n\n```csharp\n[Category(\"Smoke\")]  // instead of [Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]\n```\n\nBoth forms work with the `Category=Smoke` filter—no attribute change is required.\n\n### Key gotcha\n\nWith MTP the `&` must reach the test platform unmangled by your shell. In most CI shells, wrapping the whole `--filter` value in **double quotes** (as above) is sufficient.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"514d336a-5dfc-421f-86a5-d7fa017fcec9","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"982F:254503:183DBD:1FE82C:69FFD8EA"},"id":"0562ac85-e8a2-4a21-b814-f5ef0bdfd0ba","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:01:41.947Z","parentId":"ba57e1cc-d9b0-4f43-b338-925ea17166a8"}
